  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a lexical reachability?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "**Lexical reachability** is the ability to access a name—such as a variable, function, class, or binding—based on the program’s **lexical structure**, meaning its written source-code scope.\n\nIn simpler terms: something is *lexically reachable* from a point in code if that point is inside the scope where the name is visible.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nlet x = 10;\n\nfunction foo() {\n  let y = 20;\n\n  console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  console.log(y); // y is lexically reachable here\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\nconsole.log(y); // Error: y is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nHere:\n\n- `x` is reachable inside `foo()` because `foo` is nested inside the scope where `x` is declared.\n- `y` is only reachable inside `foo()` because it is declared there.\n- Outside `foo()`, `y` is not lexically reachable.\n\n“Lexical” means the reachability is determined by the **code layout**, not by runtime behavior. So lexical reachability is closely related to **static scope** or **lexical scope**.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "“Lexical reachability” usually refers to whether a name, variable, function, or declaration can be accessed from a particular place in source code based on the program’s lexical structure — that is, its written/nested scope.\n\nIn simpler terms: something is lexically reachable if the code at that location is allowed to “see” it because of where it is written.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`, where `x` is declared.\n\nBut here:\n\n```js\nfunction one() {\n  let x = 10;\n}\n\nfunction two() {\n  console.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n}\n```\n\n`x` is not lexically reachable from `two`, because `two` is not inside the lexical scope where `x` exists.\n\nSo, broadly:\n\n> Lexical reachability means reachability determined by the static structure of the code, not by runtime execution paths.\n\nIt is closely related to lexical scope, static scope, closures, and name resolution.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from in-context learning capability?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "“Lexical reachability” and “vocabulary coverage” refer to different ideas.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Main question |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Whether a name/word/item can be accessed or reached from a given point, often based on scope or relationships | “Can this item be reached from here?” |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | How much of a text, dataset, or language is covered by a known vocabulary list | “How many of the words are known/included?” |\n\nIn the programming sense from the earlier answer:\n\n```js\nlet x = 1;\n\nfunction f() {\n  console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n}\n```\n\nHere, **lexical reachability** is about whether `x` is accessible from a particular location in the code because of lexical scope.\n\nBy contrast, **vocabulary coverage** is common in linguistics, language learning, and NLP. For example:\n\n> A learner knows 950 of the 1,000 unique words in a text.\n\nThen their vocabulary coverage is:\n\n```text\n950 / 1000 = 95%\n```\n\nSo:\n\n- **Lexical reachability** is about accessibility from a position or context.\n- **Vocabulary coverage** is about proportion of known or included words.\n\nIn short: lexical reachability is a **scope/access** concept, while vocabulary coverage is a **quantity/coverage** concept.",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** are related in spirit—both ask whether something can be “reached”—but they apply to different kinds of structures.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Structure involved | Main question |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Whether a name/binding is accessible from a point in source code | Lexical scopes in a program | “Can this variable/function name be used here?” |\n| **Graph reachability** | Whether one node can be reached from another by following edges | A graph of nodes and edges | “Is there a path from node A to node B?” |\n\nExample of **lexical reachability**:\n\n```js\nlet x = 1;\n\nfunction f() {\n  let y = 2;\n\n  console.log(x); // reachable\n  console.log(y); // reachable\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // reachable\nconsole.log(y); // not reachable\n```\n\nHere, reachability depends on the program’s **written scope structure**.\n\nExample of **graph reachability**:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nIn this graph:\n\n- `B` is reachable from `A`\n- `C` is reachable from `A`\n- `A` is not reachable from `C`, unless there is an edge back\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n- **Lexical reachability** is a programming-language scope concept.\n- **Graph reachability** is a general mathematical/computational graph concept.\n\nThat said, lexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using a graph**. For example, scopes can be represented as nodes with edges to parent scopes. But the rules for lexical reachability are determined by language semantics, not by arbitrary graph paths.",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different concepts.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Domain | Main question |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Whether a name or binding is accessible from a particular point in source code because of lexical scope | Programming languages / static analysis | “Can this variable/function be referred to here?” |\n| **In-context learning capability** | A model’s ability to adapt its behavior from examples or instructions provided in the prompt, without changing its weights | Machine learning / large language models | “Can the model infer the task from the context?” |\n\nExample of **lexical reachability**:\n\n```js\nlet x = 10;\n\nfunction f() {\n  console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is also reachable here\n```\n\nThis is about whether `x` is visible from a certain place in the program.\n\nExample of **in-context learning**:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French:\n\ncat → chat\ndog → chien\nhouse → ?\n```\n\nA language model may infer from the examples that it should translate “house” into French and answer:\n\n```text\nmaison\n```\n\nThe model has not been retrained; it is using the examples in the prompt as context.\n\nSo the key difference is:\n\n- **Lexical reachability** is about **static accessibility of symbols in code**.\n- **In-context learning capability** is about **a model’s ability to infer patterns or tasks from prompt context**.\n\nThey are only loosely related in that both involve “context,” but the kind of context is different:\n\n- Lexical reachability uses **source-code context** and formal scoping rules.\n- In-context learning uses **prompt context** and learned statistical/semantic behavior."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"lexical reachability\": Lexical Reachability is the metric that operationalizes the Token-Substrate Hypothesis as the gap between a model's cold-state distinguishability of a term against named near-neighbors and its post-introduction distinguishability after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per (model × term × near-neighbor) cell. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged — I have read the canonical definition of “lexical reachability” you provided.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "“Lexical reachability” differs from vocabulary coverage in that it is not mainly about whether a term is present in a model’s vocabulary or corpus exposure. It is about how well a model can distinguish a term from named near-neighbors before and after being given a definition in context.\n\nIn short:\n\n| Concept | What it measures |\n|---|---|\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Whether a word/token is represented, known, or present in a vocabulary, corpus, tokenizer, lexicon, or benchmark set. |\n| **Lexical reachability** | How much a model’s ability to distinguish a term from similar named alternatives improves after a single-sentence definition. |\n\nSo vocabulary coverage is more like:\n\n> “Does the system have this word available or represented?”\n\nWhereas lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can the model acquire or sharpen the meaning of this term from a minimal contextual introduction, relative to near-neighbor terms?”\n\nFor example, a model may have vocabulary coverage for a term because the term tokenizes cleanly or appears in training data. But that does not mean the term is lexically reachable in your canonical sense. If the model still confuses it with close neighboring terms after a definition, then its lexical reachability may be low.\n\nConversely, a rare or novel term may have poor vocabulary coverage in the ordinary sense, but high lexical reachability if the model can quickly distinguish it from near-neighbors after a one-sentence definition.\n\nThe key differences are:\n\n1. **Static vs. dynamic**  \n   Vocabulary coverage is usually a static property of a lexicon, tokenizer, or dataset. Lexical reachability is a before/after measurement.\n\n2. **Presence vs. distinguishability**  \n   Coverage asks whether the term is present or representable. Lexical reachability asks whether the model can distinguish the term from named near-neighbors.\n\n3. **No-definition vs. post-definition effect**  \n   Vocabulary coverage does not require an in-context definition. Lexical reachability is specifically about the gap between cold-state distinguishability and post-introduction distinguishability.\n\n4. **Term-level vs. model × term × near-neighbor cell**  \n   Vocabulary coverage is often aggregated over words or tokens. Lexical reachability is scored per specific model, term, and near-neighbor comparison.\n\nSo the concise distinction is:\n\n> Vocabulary coverage measures whether a term is available to the system; lexical reachability measures how much more semantically distinguishable that term becomes after minimal contextual introduction.",
    "“Lexical reachability” differs from **graph reachability** because they measure entirely different kinds of access.\n\n| Concept | What it asks | Domain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Graph reachability** | “Is there a path from node A to node B?” | Graph theory, networks, program analysis, automata, databases |\n| **Lexical reachability** | “How much does a model’s distinguishability of a term from named near-neighbors improve after a one-sentence definition?” | Model evaluation, lexical semantics, in-context learning |\n\nGraph reachability is a structural/path property. If you have a graph:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nthen `C` is reachable from `A` because there is a path from `A` to `C`.\n\nLexical reachability, using your canonical definition, is not about paths between nodes. It is a metric over a **model × term × near-neighbor** cell. It compares:\n\n1. the model’s **cold-state distinguishability** of a term from a named near-neighbor, and  \n2. the model’s **post-introduction distinguishability** after the term is defined in a single sentence.\n\nSo graph reachability asks:\n\n> Can one point be reached from another through edges?\n\nLexical reachability asks:\n\n> Does a brief definition make this term more distinguishable from a specific nearby term for this model?\n\nA term could be “near” another term semantically or lexically, but lexical reachability is not the existence of a route between them. It is the measured gap between pre-definition and post-definition discriminability.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Graph reachability is about connectivity. Lexical reachability is about definition-induced improvement in semantic distinguishability.**",
    "“Lexical reachability” differs from **in-context learning capability** mainly in scope and measurement.\n\n| Concept | What it measures |\n|---|---|\n| **In-context learning capability** | A model’s general ability to use information provided in the prompt to perform a task better, without weight updates. |\n| **Lexical reachability** | A specific metric measuring the gap between a model’s cold-state distinguishability of a term from named near-neighbors and its distinguishability after a one-sentence definition is introduced. |\n\nIn-context learning is broad. It can include learning from examples, instructions, demonstrations, formatting patterns, task descriptions, labels, or definitions. For example, if a model sees three input-output examples and then correctly completes a fourth, that is in-context learning.\n\nLexical reachability is narrower. It asks something more specific:\n\n> Given a term and a named near-neighbor, how much better does the model distinguish the term after receiving a single-sentence definition?\n\nSo lexical reachability can be viewed as a specialized diagnostic of in-context lexical uptake, but it is not the same as general in-context learning.\n\nKey differences:\n\n1. **General vs. specific**  \n   In-context learning is a broad behavioral capability. Lexical reachability is a specific term-level metric.\n\n2. **Many prompt types vs. one-sentence definition**  \n   In-context learning may use demonstrations, instructions, schemas, examples, or long context. Lexical reachability specifically uses a single-sentence definition as the post-introduction intervention.\n\n3. **Task performance vs. distinguishability**  \n   In-context learning is often measured by downstream task accuracy. Lexical reachability is measured by distinguishability between a target term and named near-neighbors.\n\n4. **Aggregate ability vs. per-cell score**  \n   In-context learning is usually discussed as a model-level or task-level capability. Lexical reachability is scored per **model × term × near-neighbor** cell.\n\n5. **Learning broadly vs. resolving lexical contrast**  \n   A model may be good at in-context learning in general but still have low lexical reachability for a particular term if the definition does not help it distinguish that term from a close neighbor.\n\nConcise distinction:\n\n> In-context learning is the broad ability to use prompt-provided information; lexical reachability is a specific metric for how much a one-sentence definition improves a model’s ability to distinguish a term from named near-neighbors."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "“Lexical reachability” usually means **what names, declarations, or variables are accessible from a particular point in source code based on lexical/static scope rules**.\n\nIn other words, something is lexically reachable if the code can “see” it because of where it appears textually in the program.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`, and lexical scoping allows inner scopes to access names from outer scopes.\n\nContrast:\n\n```js\nfunction a() {\n  let x = 10;\n}\n\nfunction b() {\n  console.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n}\n```\n\nHere `x` is not lexically reachable from `b`, because `b` is not textually inside `a`.\n\nSo, broadly:\n\n> **Lexical reachability = availability of a name/entity according to the program’s written scope structure, not according to runtime control flow.**\n\nIt is closely related to **lexical scope**, **static scope**, and **closures**.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "They are different ideas, even though both use “lexical.”\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a particular name or item can be accessed from a given place based on structure.\n\nIn programming:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is reachable from `inner` because of lexical/static scope.\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this name be accessed from here?”\n\nIt is usually a **yes/no relationship** between a location and a declaration.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Vocabulary coverage\n**Vocabulary coverage** is about how much of a text or corpus is covered by a known vocabulary.\n\nFor example, if a learner knows 900 out of 1,000 words in a text, their vocabulary coverage is 90%.\n\nSo vocabulary coverage asks:\n\n> “What percentage of the words are known, included, or recognized?”\n\nIt is usually a **quantitative measure**.\n\n---\n\n### Simple contrast\n\n| Concept | Main question | Domain | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lexical reachability | “Can this name be accessed from here?” | Programming / scoping | Can `inner()` access variable `x`? |\n| Vocabulary coverage | “How many words are known or included?” | Linguistics / NLP / language learning | Does a vocabulary list cover 95% of a text? |\n\nSo, in short:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about access according to structure. Vocabulary coverage is about proportion of words known or represented.**",
    "They differ mainly in **what kind of “reachability” is being discussed**.\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about access according to **lexical/static structure** of code.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Can this name/declaration be seen from this point in the source code?”\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable from inside `inner` because `inner` is textually nested inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability depends on things like:\n\n- scopes\n- nesting\n- declarations\n- imports/modules\n- name resolution rules\n\n---\n\n### 2. Graph reachability\n\n**Graph reachability** is a general graph-theoretic concept.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Is there a path from node A to node B in a graph?”\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\n`C` is reachable from `A` because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nGraph reachability applies to many domains:\n\n- social networks\n- dependency graphs\n- control-flow graphs\n- call graphs\n- file systems\n- web links\n- compiler analysis\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Depends on | Domain |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lexical reachability | “Can this name be accessed from here?” | Language scope rules | Programming languages / compilers |\n| Graph reachability | “Is there a path between these nodes?” | Edges in a graph | General math / CS |\n\n---\n\n### Important connection\n\nLexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using graph reachability**.\n\nFor example, a compiler might represent scopes as a graph:\n\n```text\ninner scope → outer scope → global scope\n```\n\nThen checking whether `x` is lexically reachable may involve searching that graph.\n\nBut conceptually:\n\n> **Graph reachability is the general idea of path existence. Lexical reachability is a specific programming-language idea about whether a declaration is visible from a source-code location.**",
    "They are quite different concepts.\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether something is accessible because of the **static structure of code or text**.\n\nIn programming, it asks:\n\n> “Can this variable, function, or declaration be seen from this point in the program?”\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is textually nested inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability is mostly about:\n\n- scope\n- nesting\n- visibility\n- name resolution\n- static program structure\n\n---\n\n### 2. In-context learning capability\n\n**In-context learning capability** is a property of large language models.\n\nIt refers to the model’s ability to learn or infer a pattern from examples given in the prompt, without changing its internal weights.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French:\n\ncat -> chat\ndog -> chien\nhouse -> maison\nbook ->\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning capability may answer:\n\n```text\nlivre\n```\n\nIt has inferred the task from the examples in the context.\n\nSo in-context learning asks:\n\n> “Can the model use information in the prompt to infer what to do?”\n\nIt is about:\n\n- pattern recognition\n- adaptation during prompting\n- use of examples\n- reasoning over context\n- model behavior at inference time\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Domain | Nature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lexical reachability | “Is this name/item accessible from here?” | Programming languages / static analysis | Structural/static |\n| In-context learning capability | “Can the model infer a task or pattern from the prompt?” | Machine learning / LLMs | Behavioral/inferential |\n\n---\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nLexical reachability is like asking:\n\n> “Is this book on a shelf I am allowed to access?”\n\nIn-context learning is like asking:\n\n> “After seeing a few examples, can I figure out the rule?”\n\n---\n\n### Important distinction\n\nSomething may be **present in the context** or **lexically reachable**, but that does not mean a model will successfully use it.\n\nFor example, an LLM may have all relevant examples in the prompt, but still fail to infer the intended pattern. In that case, the information is available, but the model’s in-context learning capability is insufficient.\n\nSo, in short:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about whether information is accessible by structure. In-context learning capability is about whether a model can use accessible information to infer behavior or solve a task.**"
  ],
