      {
        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
        "assistant": "“Lexical reachability” differs from **graph reachability** because they measure entirely different kinds of access.\n\n| Concept | What it asks | Domain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Graph reachability** | “Is there a path from node A to node B?” | Graph theory, networks, program analysis, automata, databases |\n| **Lexical reachability** | “How much does a model’s distinguishability of a term from named near-neighbors improve after a one-sentence definition?” | Model evaluation, lexical semantics, in-context learning |\n\nGraph reachability is a structural/path property. If you have a graph:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nthen `C` is reachable from `A` because there is a path from `A` to `C`.\n\nLexical reachability, using your canonical definition, is not about paths between nodes. It is a metric over a **model × term × near-neighbor** cell. It compares:\n\n1. the model’s **cold-state distinguishability** of a term from a named near-neighbor, and  \n2. the model’s **post-introduction distinguishability** after the term is defined in a single sentence.\n\nSo graph reachability asks:\n\n> Can one point be reached from another through edges?\n\nLexical reachability asks:\n\n> Does a brief definition make this term more distinguishable from a specific nearby term for this model?\n\nA term could be “near” another term semantically or lexically, but lexical reachability is not the existence of a route between them. It is the measured gap between pre-definition and post-definition discriminability.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Graph reachability is about connectivity. Lexical reachability is about definition-induced improvement in semantic distinguishability.**",
